{"title":"Now you can buy a Colnago C68 gravel bike","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/colnago-c68-gravel-bike","date":1706778000000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/colnago-c68-gravel-bike\">Now you can buy a Colnago C68 gravel bike</a></p>\n\n<p>Not content with offering its C68 in road, all-road and titanium models, Colnago has launched a gravel variant of its handbuilt-in-Italy C68.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The new C68 Gravel has a shorter reach and taller stack than the C68 Allroad, as well as wider tyre clearance. It’s also specced with a new, wider design of the Colnago CC.01 one-piece carbon cockpit.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Colnago will offer three builds, priced at €7,250 with Shimano GRX RX820, €8,690 with SRAM Force XPLR and €12,010 (£11,099) with SRAM Red XPLR as well as a €5,935 (£5,269) frameset-only option.  </p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/best-all-road-bikes\">Best all-road bikes 2024 reviewed</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/colnago-c68-road-review\">Colnago C68 Road review</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tadej-pogacar-bike-2\">Tadej Pogačar’s bike: Sub-7kg Colnago V4Rs for the 2023 Tour de France</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/best-gravel-bike\">Best of the best gravel bikes 2024: Cyclist’s top-rated gravel and adventure bikes</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article></div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <span></span><span></span><span></span>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        </div>\n\n\n<h2>Greater off-road capability</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The C68 Gravel has clearance for 42mm tyres, setting it apart from the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/colnago-c68-allroad\" target=\"_blank\">C68 Allroad</a>, which can accommodate 35mm rubber and the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/colnago-c68-road-review\" target=\"_blank\">C68 Road</a> variant, which stops at 30mm. Colnago says that the C68 Allroad is geared towards dirt roads, as well as road riding, while the C68 Gravel takes things further off-road.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>As is usual with gravel bikes, there’s a shorter reach and higher stack than on Colnago’s C series road bikes. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"572\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-geo-chart-970x572.jpeg\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-geo-chart-970x572.jpeg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-geo-chart-300x177.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-geo-chart-768x453.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-geo-chart-750x442.jpeg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-geo-chart-1140x672.jpeg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-geo-chart.jpeg 1451w\" /><figcaption>Colnago</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Colnago says that the C68 Gravel’s <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/road-bike-geometry-handling\" target=\"_blank\">geometry </a>also differs from its <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/colnago-g3-x-review\" target=\"_blank\">G3-X</a> race-oriented gravel bike, with the C68 Gravel designed more for stability and smooth riding. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>It incorporates a longer front centre than the G3-X, hence increasing the wheelbase, and a 70.5° head tube angle. The reach is also longer than in the G3-X, so you can spec a shorter stem.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-17-970x647.jpg\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-17-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-17-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-17-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-17-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-17-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-17-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-17-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-17-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-17-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-17-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Colnago</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Colnago supplies the bike with a new, wider CC.01 Wide carbon one-piece bar/stem with 400mm width at the hoods and 460mm at the drops. There are five effective stem lengths available from 80mm up to 120mm, all with the same width, 120mm drop and internal cable/hose routing.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The C68 Gravel frame is compatible with <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/power-of-one-the-rise-of-the-1x-groupset\" target=\"_blank\">single-ring groupsets</a> only, although this can be mechanical as well as electronic, allowing Colnago to offer 12-speed <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/shimano-grx-rx820-groupset-review\" target=\"_blank\">Shimano GRX RX820</a> and <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/sram-groupsets-buyers-guide\" target=\"_blank\">SRAM Red/Force XPLR</a> specs, all with a T47 bottom bracket.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The frame has also been designed so that you can swap out the rigid fork for a suspension fork. </p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Handbuilt lugged fabrication</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-1-970x647.jpg\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-1-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-1-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-1-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-1-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-1-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-1-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-1-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-1-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-1-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/02/Colnago-C68-Gravel-Dettagli-still-life-ambientati-1-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Colnago</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>As with the other C Series Colnago bikes, the C68 Gravel is handbuilt in Italy and uses a sanded and glued lugged construction rather than the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/carbon-jargon-what-does-it-all-mean\" target=\"_blank\">monocoque </a>method more common in carbon bike frames. Colnago says that this results in a clean look to the frame, with flush joints between the different tubes. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>According to Colnago, ‘The C68 Gravel isn’t a mere gravel bike, it’s the epitome of Italian craftsmanship, meticulously crafted for cyclists who seek the ultimate riding experience. For those who yearn for the thrill of pure speed on the wildest gravel roads – and everything in between, but also demand more than just a carbon frame – they seek a bike with a soul, steeped in heritage.’</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Specs, sizes and prices</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"644\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/01/Colnago-C68-Gravel-970x644.jpeg\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/01/Colnago-C68-Gravel-970x644.jpeg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/01/Colnago-C68-Gravel-300x199.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/01/Colnago-C68-Gravel-768x510.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/01/Colnago-C68-Gravel-1536x1020.jpeg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/01/Colnago-C68-Gravel-2048x1360.jpeg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/01/Colnago-C68-Gravel-750x498.jpeg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/01/Colnago-C68-Gravel-1140x757.jpeg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/01/Colnago-C68-Gravel-465x310.jpeg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/01/Colnago-C68-Gravel-620x413.jpeg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/01/Colnago-C68-Gravel-350x233.jpeg 350w\" /><figcaption>Colnago </figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Colnago will offer the C68 Gravel in five sizes and two colours – green or black – all with its sloping frame geometry: 450, 480, 510, 540 and 570. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>While the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/colnago-c68-road-review\" target=\"_blank\">C68 Road</a> and Allroad bikes have starting prices of €8,970 and the titanium bike is priced from €13,000, the C68 Gravel is something of a bargain, with Colnago offering specs from €7,250. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Complete bikes will be offered with a range of Fulcrum or Zipp wheels, all fitted with Pirelli Cinturato Gravel H TLR 40mm tyres. There’s a frameset-only option, priced at €5,935.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>In the UK, you’ll be able to buy the top SRAM Red XPLR spec for £11,099 or the frameset for £5,269.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>Browse our crop of the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/best-gravel-bike\" target=\"_blank\">best gravel bikes we’ve reviewed</a>.</em></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/colnago-c68-gravel-bike\">Now you can buy a Colnago C68 gravel bike</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a>.</p>","author":"pnorman","siteTitle":"Cyclist.co.uk","siteHash":"561486e7070fa5351de9318ad0fa26c2a39332acba5fc7c7d1694a01d53d431e","entryHash":"831c021b170c961e327a806e9efcc46eee646249e8f21e94d811ee2999523ed8","category":"Cycling"}